STA141A Milestone2: Decision-Making: Predictive Modeling of Mouse Behavioral Outcomes Using Integrated Neural Activity and Stimulus Features

Kefan Pan

2025-02-13

Abstract: This study analyzes neural recordings from mouse visual cortex during a decision-making task (Steinmetz et al., 2019) to predict trial outcomes (success/failure) Introduction:Neurodecoding technology can advance brain-computer interfaces and neurological disease research, with understanding how the brain makes decisions at its core.I use data from the Steinmetz team’s 2019 mouse experiments contains: Timing of visual cortex neuron firing over 400 milliseconds.Difference between left and right screen grayscales (0-1 gradient).Positive and negative feedback for each choice (success = 1, failure = -1). I aim to develop predictive models adapted to new experimental days and establish a scheme for integrating data across time.

  n_neurons = rep(0, n.session),

  tmp <- sessions[[i]] 
  meta[i, 1] <- tmp$mouse_name
  meta[i, 2] <- tmp$date_exp   
  meta[i, 3] <- length(unique(tmp$brain_area))  
  meta[i, 4] <- dim(tmp$spks[[1]])[1]

create a matrix and combine information in each trail.

i.s = 2
i.t = 1
spk.trial = sessions[[i.s]]$spks[[i.t]]
area=sessions[[i.s]]$brain_area
spk.count <- apply(spk.trial, 1, sum)
spk.average.tapply <- tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
tmp <- data.frame(area = area,spikes = spk.count)
spk.average.dplyr <- tmp %>%
  group_by(area) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(spikes))

n.trial <- length(sessions[[i.s]]$feedback_type)
n.area <- length(unique(sessions[[i.s]]$brain_area))

trial.summary <- matrix(nrow = n.trial, ncol = n.area + 1 + 2 + 1)

average_spike_area <- function(i.t, this_session) {
  spk.trial <- this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area <- this_session$brain_area
  spk.count <- apply(spk.trial, 1, sum)
  tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
}
this_session <- sessions[[i.s]]
for (i.t in 1:n.trial) {
  trial.summary[i.t, ] <- c(
    average_spike_area(i.t, this_session),
    sessions[[i.s]]$feedback_type[i.t],
    sessions[[i.s]]$contrast_left[i.t],
    sessions[[i.s]]$contrast_right[i.t],
    i.t
  )
}
colnames(trial.summary) <- c(
  names(average_spike_area(1, this_session = sessions[[i.s]])),
  "feedback", "left_contrast", "right_contrast", "id"
) 
trial.summary <- as_tibble(trial.summary)
trial.summary <- na.omit(trial.summary)
print(trial.summary)

Visualization

area.col <- rainbow(n = n.area, alpha = 0.7)
plot(x = 1, y = 0, col = 'white', 
     xlim = c(0, n.trial), ylim = c(0.5, 2.2), 
     xlab = "Trials", ylab = "Average spike counts", 
     main = paste("Spikes per area in Session", i.s))
for (i in 1:n.area) {
  lines(y = na.omit(trial.summary[[i]]), x = trial.summary$id[!is.na(trial.summary[[i]])], col = area.col[i], lty = 2, lwd = 1)
  lines(smooth.spline(trial.summary$id[!is.na(trial.summary[[i]])],na.omit(trial.summary[[i]])), col= area.col[i], lwd = 3)
}
legend("topright", 
       legend = colnames(trial.summary)[1:n.area], 
       col = area.col, 
       lty = 1, 
       cex = 0.8)

For this plot, we can find out peaks/troughs may correlate with trial outcomes (success/failure). And there exist some areas show consistently lower activity, while others exhibit higher variability, indicating functional specialization.

Data Integration

integrated_data <- list()
for (i in 1:18) {
  session_data <- sessions[[i]]
  trials <- session_data$trials
  session_features <- lapply(trials, function(trial) {

    area_activity <- sapply(sessions, function(sessions) {
      neurons_in_area <- which(session_data$brain_area == area)
      mean(rowSums(trial$spks[neurons_in_area, ])) 
    })
    data.frame(
      contrast_left = trial$contrast_left,
      contrast_right = trial$contrast_right,
      t(area_activity),
      feedback = trial$feedback_type
    )
  })
}
